## 5. Important Root Directories in Ubuntu Linux

Ubuntu Linux organizes files using a root directory `/`. Everything starts from this location.

### Important directories

| Directory | Purpose                                          |
| --------- | ------------------------------------------------ |
| `/home`   | Stores user files and personal folders           |
| `/etc`    | Stores system configuration files                |
| `/var`    | Stores changing data like logs and service files |
| `/bin`    | Contains essential user commands                 |
| `/sbin`   | Contains system administration commands          |
| `/usr`    | Stores installed programs and shared files       |
| `/tmp`    | Temporary files                                  |
| `/root`   | Home directory for the root user                 |
| `/boot`   | Files needed to start the system                 |
| `/dev`    | Device files such as drives and terminals        |
| `/proc`   | System and process information                   |
| `/opt`    | Optional third-party software                    |

### Example usage

```bash
cd /var/log
ls
```

This lets you view system log files.

```bash
cd /etc
ls
```

This shows configuration files used by the system.

